<span class="name"><a name="34005"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#22:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Seboa Nivlac</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=34005&amp;sid=af55f71e6f117ba766badcf16be9b327#34005"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Thu Feb 13, 2003 3:01 am</font><span class="gen"><br>
	<span class="gensmall">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;----</span><br>

<span class="postbody">After disscussing this with my brother, (he's a 62 wizard who for the first time last night experienced PoS) I have to think that Paragon of the Spirit is exactly why we will never get MGB.  And if we did it would not work with PoS.
<br />

<br />
Just in terms of balance, a MGB PoS is out of whack.
<br />

<br />
Now one of the most difficult things to do is to assign a value to mana, however for the sake of argument I am going to give it a semi arbitrary value of 3 damage is capable of being done for each point of mana in a raid force.  Either damage is being done by nukes, dots, or keeping the MT alive and thus the raid continuing onward.
<br />

<br />
The problem is not with small, 12-24 person raids.  No, problems arise when raids begin to become big.  A MGB PoS would become too exploitable, too valuable, to keep in check.
<br />

<br />
Lets suppose a moderately large raid force of 36 people.  Now lets be pessimistic and suppose that half of those people would not benefit from mana regeneration, either they don't burn through spells that quickly, or have no mana whatsoever.
<br />

<br />
18 people, receiving even 480 mana is 8640 points of mana.  Going back to our selected value of 3 damage per mana, that would effectively allow a MGB PoS to cause 25920 points of damage directly and indirectly.  And this is NOT even considering PoS with SCR3.  On a 60 person raid (which is the most the raid window allows) and still assuming the mana portion is useful to only half of the raid, the total would be 14400 mana or a whooping 43200 damage.
<br />

<br />
Mana burn in its prime optimisticly caused 17000 points of damage, but this was deemed too much.  Now it does 9000 on a well equipped wizard.  Let's compare AA expenditures for a moment.
<br />

<br />
Mana burn is 9 points.
<br />
Mass Group Buff is 9 points (for classes that receive it) and Paragon of the Spirit is 5 points.  
<br />

<br />
It would take almost 3 mana burning wizards or 27 AA to equal the damage the Beastlord could cause with 14 on a 36 person raid.  On a 60 person raid it would require almost 5!  
<br />

<br />
Now I know there are some differences between manaburn and a MGB PoS
<br />

<br />
MB dosen't need a large raid to do a lot of damage
<br />
Yet the value of a MGB PoS would increase with every caster added
<br />

<br />
PoS also restores hit points, which only adds to its value
<br />
MB can be fairly easily used in any given raid, in order to take advantage of the hp regen, clerics would have to adjust their healing tactics.
<br />

<br />
We will never see a MGB AA that is compatible with PoS.  It would be too unbalancing, not for the small force, but for the large raid.  The potential for exploit would be too great.  I know we all want something to really pull us into high demand for raids, but MGB PoS would be a surefire way to get some part of us smacked hard with a nerf bat..
<br />

<br />
-Seboa</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
